	<div class="posts">
	<a name="94181084">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<h1>Systems Architecture and Design</h1><h2>Development of Software 
    Engineering Practice</h2><h3>When do we demonstrate that we are engineers?</h3>
    I blogged this in the midst of a strenous Software Engineering module in my 
    on-line M.Sc in IT program.&nbsp; The problem of using the term, with its 
    licensing implications, versus <i>being</i> a software engineer is also an 
    interesting one.&nbsp; What I noticed about the course on Software 
    Engineering was that its conduct, and the use of a team project, brought up 
    every software-engineering antipattern that seems to exist.&nbsp; Since it 
    is our experience that will matter, I wonder if the message of the delivery 
    of the course will be one that has the participants be software-engineering 
    averse.&nbsp; Or maybe this is the powerful lesson that demonstrates both 
    the challenge and the promise.&nbsp; We&#39;ll see ...<br /><br /><a href="http://www.ima.umn.edu/~arnold/disasters/ariane.html">
    The Explosion of the Ariane 5</a>.&nbsp; This article by Douglas Arnold 
    provides highlights of the Ariane 5 loss, and links to other information on 
    the software-related failure. Linked from the discussion assignments for our 
    final week of an on-line M.Sc Software Engineering module.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#94181084">Sunday, May 11, 
    2003</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="94180496">&nbsp;</a><br>
