	<div class="posts">
	<a name="94179287">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<b>Computer Software Engineers</b>.&nbsp; From the Bureau of Labor 
    Statistics &quot;Occupational Outlook Handbook.&quot; There was data from 2000 and 
    2001, so the dot-com implosion had not been fully felt yet.&nbsp; At that 
    time, software-engineering was distinct from programming, although an SE is 
    expected to have been/be a strong programmer. There were some useful links 
    on certification and detailed career information.&nbsp;&nbsp; A find by 
    classmate Annita Zirki.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis on <a href="#94179287">Sunday, May 11, 
    2003</a></span><br>
	<span class="byline">updated by Dennis on <a href="#94179287">Monday, March 
    25, 2013</a></span><br>
    The ca. 2000 Bureau of Labor Statistics page has become obsolete.&nbsp; The 
    interesting data is now for
    <a href="http://www.bls.gov/ooh/computer-and-information-technology/software-developers.htm">
    Software Developers</a> (based on 2010 data) as well as other
    <a href="http://www.bls.gov/ooh/computer-and-information-technology/home.htm">
    Computer and Information Technology</a> occupations.&nbsp; There is 2009 
    data for <a href="http://www.bls.gov/oes/2009/may/oes151032.htm">Computer 
    Software Engineers, Systems Software</a> and
    <a href="http://www.bls.gov/oes/2009/may/oes151031.htm">Computer Software 
    Engineers, Applications</a>.&nbsp; The obsolescence of the earlier data and 
    removal of that page was pointed out today by Stephanie Hill, along with 
    recommendation of this
    <a href="http://www.onlinecollege.org/jobs/technology/software-developer/">
    Software Developer Career Profile</a>.<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp; [It is amazing to me that these aging pages, which I have succeeded 
    in keeping on-line, are still found useful.&nbsp; To receive an update in my 
    mail was all the more exciting.&nbsp; Than you, Stephanie.]</div>
